{"id":"1412.5055","submitter":"Ashwin Ganesan","authors":"Ashwin Ganesan","title":"On the automorphism group of a Johnson graph","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Johnson graph $J(n,i)$ is defined to the graph whose vertex set is the\nset of all $i$-element subsets of $\\{1,\\ldots,n\\}$, and two vertices are joined\nwhenever the cardinality of their intersection is equal to $i-1$. In Ramras and\nDonovan [\\emph{SIAM J. Discrete Math}, 25(1): 267-270, 2011], it is conjectured\nthat if $n=2i$, then the automorphism group of the Johnson graph $J(n,i)$ is\n$S_n \\times \\langle T \\rangle$, where $T$ is the complementation map $A \\mapsto\n\\{1,\\ldots,n\\} \\setminus A$. We resolve this conjecture in the affirmative. The\nproof uses only elementary group theory and is based on an analysis of the\nclique structure of the graph.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 9 Dec 2014 14:39:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-12-17"}
